'''Francisco de Avila''' (1573&ndash;1647) was a [[South American]] [[priest]] and early student of native customs.

Avila was born in Cuzco.  He was [[curate]] or [[vicar]] in the [[Huarochirí Province|province of Huarochiri]] of [[Peru]], later curate at [[Huánuco]], and finally [[Canon (priest)|Canon]] of the Church of La Plata (now [[Sucre]]), in [[Bolivia]]. He was one of the most active investigators of Indian rites and customs of his time.  He died in Lima.

==Works==
In 1608 he wrote a treatise of the "''Errors, False Gods, and Other Superstitions of the Indians of the Provinces of Huarochiri, Mama, and Chaclla''", of which only the first six chapters are known to exist and have been translated into English. It is a contribution to the knowledge of the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Peruvian Indians]] and their lore.

In 1611 Avila wrote a report on the Indians of Huánuco in eastern Peru, of which [[Huarochirí Manuscript|the unpublished manuscript]] is extant. These works contain apologetics on the destruction of fetishes and other objects of worship, for example by [[Pablo José Arriaga]].

