{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Nyah Kur |image= |image_caption= |population = 2000<ref name=ConsArticle>{{cite journal|last1=Prasert |first1=Supisara |last2=Pansila |first2=Virat |last3=Lasunon |first3=On-Uma |year=2009 |title=Guidelines and Methods for Conservation, Revitalization and Development of the Traditions and Customs of Nyah Kur Ethnic Group for Tourism in the Province of Chaiyapum in Northeast Thailand |journal=The Social Sciences |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=174–179 |publisher= |doi= |url=http://www.medwelljournals.com/fulltext/?doi=sscience.2009.174.179 |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>-6000<ref name=ThongDict>[[Theraphan Luangthongkum|Theraphan L. Thongkum]]. (1984). ''Nyah Kur (Chao bon)–Thai–English dictionary''. Monic language studies, vol. 2. Bangkok, Thailand: Chulalongkorn University Printing House. {{ISBN|974-563-785-8}}</ref><ref name=Prem>{{cite journal|last1=Premsrirat |first1=Suwilai |year=2002 |title=The Future of Nyah Kur |journal=Collected papers on Southeast Asian and Pacific languages |pages=155–165 |editor1-first=Robert S. |editor1-last=Bauer |publisher=Australian National Univ., Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies}}</ref> |popplace = {{flag|Thailand}} |pop1 = |languages = [[Nyah Kur language|Nyah Kur]], [[Thai language|Thai]], [[Isan language|Isan]] |rels = Predominately [[Theravada Buddhism]], traditional [[Animism]], [[Christian]] |related = [[Mon people|Mon]], [[Khmer people|Khmer]], [[Kuy language|Kuy]] and other [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic people]] of [[ethnic groups of Southeast Asia|Southeast Asia]]. }}
The '''Nyah Kur''' (known in [[Thai language|Thai]] as {{lang|th|[[wikt:ชาวบน|ชาวบน]]}}, ''Chao Bon'') are an [[ethnic group]] native to [[Thailand]] in [[Southeast Asia]]. Closely related to the [[Mon people]], the Nyah Kur are the descendants of the Mon of [[Dvaravati]] who did not flee westward or assimilate when their empire fell under the influence of the [[Khmer Empire|Khmer]] when [[Suryavarman I]] gained the throne in the early 11th century.<ref name=PanHla>{{cite book |last=Hla |first=Nai Pan |authorlink= |title=The Significant Role of the Mon Language and Culture in Southeast Asia (part 1) |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/34786983/8/REMNANTS-OF-THE-DVARAVATI-OLD-MON-PEOPLE |accessdate=18 September 2013 |year=1992 |publisher=Institute for the Study of Cultures of Asia and Africa, Tokyo University of Foreign Studies |location=Tokyo, Japan |isbn= |page=}}</ref>
==History== The Mon were believed to be one of the earliest people of continental Southeast Asia where they founded some of the earliest recorded civilizations in the region including the Dvaravati in Central Thailand, Sri Gotapura in Central Laos, [[Hariphunchai]] in Northern Thailand and the [[Thaton Kingdom]]. Dvaravati was among the first to receive Theravada missionaries from Sri Lanka in contrast to Hindu contemporaries, the Khmers and Chams. The Mon adapted the [[Pallava script]] to their language and the oldest Mon script was found in a cave in modern Saraburi dating around 550 AD. At the turn of the first millennium, the Mon came under constant pressure due to the [[Tai people|Tai]] migrations from the north and Khmer invasions from the east. When Suryavarman I, the [[Khmer people|Khmer]] heir to the throne of the [[Lavo Kingdom]], also became ruler of the [[Khmer Empire]], the vast majority of the Mon of Dvaravati fled west to other Mon lands, were taken as slaves or assimilated to the new culture.<ref name=PanHla/>
However a small remnant remained in the remote jungles of the [[Khorat Plateau]].<ref name=ConsArticle/> Little is known of their history. When they were discovered by western scholars in the early 20th century, it was variously assumed that they were part of the [[Lawa people|Lawa]] or [[Kuy people|Kuy]] ethnic groups. It was not until 1970 that their language was determined to be directly descended from [[Old Mon]], and in fact, more similar to Old Mon than the modern Mon of their brethren in present-day Burma and Western Thailand.<ref name=PanHla/> Although Nyah Kur and modern Mon are not mutually intelligible and the [[endonym]] ''Mon'' is unknown to the Nyah Kur, having remained isolated in the mountains between Central and Northeastern Thailand allowed the Nyah Kur to maintain their own ethnic identity which developed independently from the Mon during the last thousand years yet in some respects shows remarkable similarity to modern Mon culture.<ref name=ConsArticle/><ref name=PanHla/>
Today, the Nyah Kur live in small villages distributed in a north-south strip that crosses [[Phetchabun Province|Phetchabun]], [[Nakhon Ratchasima Province|Nakhon Ratchasima]] and [[Chaiyaphum Province|Chaiyaphum]] provinces, the majority living in Chaiyaphum. The Thai refer to them as ชาวบน meaning "upper people" or "sky people". Their self-designation is ''Nyah Kur'', which in the Nyah Kur language means "mountain folk" and in modern Mon translates to "hill plantation people".<ref name=PanHla/>
==Language== The [[Nyah Kur language]], as a direct descendant of Old Mon, is a sister language to the [[Mon language]] of [[Burma]], the two of which constitute the only languages of the [[Monic languages|Monic]] branch of the [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic language family]].<ref name=SEALANG>Southeast Asian Languages [http://sealang.net/mk/monic.htm Mon-Khmer Languages Project]</ref> A 2006 estimate places the number of speakers at approximately 1500 people with no monolinguals.<ref name=ethnologue>Nyah Kur [http://www.ethnologue.com/language/cbn reference] at Ethnologue (17th ed., 2013)</ref> The dialects spoken in Phetchabun and Nakhon Ratchasima have limited intelligibility with that of Chaiyaphum and are nearly extinct. Even in Chaiyaphum, the language is spoken mostly among older Nyah Kur, while others prefer to identify as Thai and speak either the local [[Isan language]] or the national [[Thai language|Thai]] standard.<ref name=ethnologue/> Nyah Kur no longer has its own script and when written, employs the [[Thai alphabet]] is used. In 1984, a Nyah Kur-Thai-English dictionary was published.
==Culture== In modern times, the Nyah Kur have had increasing contact with the surrounding Thai and Kuy population resulting modernization, migration and integration of cultures. Nyah Kur villages today are a mix of ethnic Nyah Kur and Thai-Lao families.<ref name=ConsArticle/> The Nyah Kur were historically Animists but today most practice Theravada Buddhism although traditional spirits, including Jao Paw Kun Dahn and Jao Paw Samian, are still worshiped.<ref name=ConsArticle/> The ''Pah Re Re'', a traditional courting celebration similar to that of the Mon,<ref name=PanHla/> is still practiced, usually around the time of the Thai [[Songkran (Thailand)|Songkran]].<ref name=ConsArticle/>
